The article discusses the establishment of the Organ Mountains-Desert Peaks National Monument in southern New Mexico. The area is known for its beautiful landscape and significant scientific, historic, and prehistoric resources. It contains artifacts, rock art, dwellings, and other evidence of Native peoples, as well as evidence of the region's early occupants transitioning from roaming hunters to semi-permanent villagers. The Organ Mountains also contain ancient dwellings and caves, while the area was also significant during battles among the Apaches, Spanish, Mexicans, and Americans, as well as during the Civil War. The area is rich in geological features, such as volcanic fields, lava flows, and ancient footprints. It is also home to diverse plant and animal species, including endemic and special status species. The establishment of the monument aims to preserve its cultural, historic, and scientific values and protect its natural resources.